[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] The concept of angles between lines (in the plane or in space), between two planes (*dihedral angle*) or between a line and a plane can be generalized to arbitrary dimensions.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] This generalization was first discussed by Camille Jordan.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] For any pair of flats in a Euclidean space of arbitrary dimension one can define a set of mutual angles which are invariant under isometric transformation of the Euclidean space.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] If the flats do not intersect, their shortest distance is one more invariant.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] These angles are called **canonical** or **principal**.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] The concept of angles can be generalized to pairs of flats in a finite-dimensional inner product space over the complex numbers.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] Let F and G be flats of dimensions k and l in the n -dimensional Euclidean space $E^{n}$ .
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] By definition, a translation of F or G does not alter their mutual angles.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] If F and G do not intersect, they will do so upon any translation of G which maps some point in G to some point in F .
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] It can therefore be assumed without loss of generality that F and G intersect.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] Jordan calls these coordinates **canonical**.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] By definition, the angles $\theta _{i}$ are the **angles** between F and G .
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] For these equations to determine the five non-negative integers completely, besides the dimensions $n,k$ and $\ell$ and the number $\alpha$ of angles $\theta _{i}$ , the non-negative integer $\sigma$ must be given.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] This is the number of coordinates $y_{i}$ , whose corresponding axes are those lying entirely within both F and G .
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] The integer $\sigma$ is thus the dimension of $F\cap G$ .
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] The set of angles $\theta _{i}$ may be supplemented with $\sigma$ angles 0 to indicate that $F\cap G$ has that dimension.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] Jordan's proof applies essentially unaltered when $E^{n}$ is replaced with the n -dimensional inner product space $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ over the complex numbers.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] Now let F and G be subspaces of the n -dimensional inner product space over the real or complex numbers.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] Geometrically, F and G are flats, so Jordan's definition of mutual angles applies.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] Being related to canonical coordinates, these basic vectors may be called **canonical**.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] When $a_{i},i=1,\dots ,k$ denote the canonical basic vectors for F and $b_{i},i=1,\dots ,l$ the canonical basic vectors for G then the inner product $\langle a_{i},b_{j}\rangle$ vanishes for any pair of i and j except the following ones.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] With the above ordering of the basic vectors, the matrix of the inner products $\langle a_{i},b_{j}\rangle$ is thus diagonal.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] The diagonal matrix elements $\langle a_{i},b_{i}\rangle$ are the singular values of the latter matrix.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] The variational characterization of singular values and vectors implies as a special case a variational characterization of the angles between subspaces and their associated canonical vectors.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] This characterization includes the angles 0 and $\pi /2$ introduced above and orders the angles by increasing value.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] It can be given the form of the below alternative definition.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] In this context, it is customary to talk of **principal** angles and vectors.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] where $\langle \cdot ,\cdot \rangle$ is the inner product and $\|\cdot \|$ the induced norm.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] This means that the principal angles $(\theta _{1},\ldots ,\theta _{k})$ form a set of minimized angles between the two subspaces, and the principal vectors in each subspace are orthogonal to each other.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] Geometrically, subspaces are flats (points, lines, planes etc.) that include the origin, thus any two subspaces intersect at least in the origin.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] Two two-dimensional subspaces ${\mathcal {U}}$ and ${\mathcal {W}}$ generate a set of two angles.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] In a three-dimensional Euclidean space, the subspaces ${\mathcal {U}}$ and ${\mathcal {W}}$ are either identical, or their intersection forms a line.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] In the latter case, only $\theta _{1}=0$ , where vectors $u_{1}$ and $w_{1}$ are on the line of the intersection ${\mathcal {U}}\cap {\mathcal {W}}$ and have the same direction.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] The angle $\theta _{2}>0$ will be the angle between the subspaces ${\mathcal {U}}$ and ${\mathcal {W}}$ in the orthogonal complement to ${\mathcal {U}}\cap {\mathcal {W}}$ .
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] Imagining the angle between two planes in 3D, one intuitively thinks of the largest angle, $\theta _{2}>0$ .
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] The notion of the angles and some of the variational properties can be naturally extended to arbitrary inner products and subspaces with infinite dimensions.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] Historically, the principal angles and vectors first appear in the context of canonical correlation and were originally computed using SVD of corresponding covariance matrices.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] However, as first noticed in, the canonical correlation is related to the cosine of the principal angles, which is ill-conditioned for small angles, leading to very inaccurate computation of highly correlated principal vectors in finite precision computer arithmetic.
[src:canonical-correlation/angles-between-flats] The combined technique is implemented in open-source libraries Octave and SciPy and contributed and to MATLAB.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] In statistics, **canonical-correlation analysis** (**CCA**), also called **canonical variates analysis**, is a way of inferring information from cross-covariance matrices.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] If we have two vectors *X* = (*X*1, ..., *X**n*) and *Y* = (*Y*1, ..., *Y**m*) of random variables, and there are correlations among the variables, then canonical-correlation analysis will find linear combinations of *X* and *Y* that have a maximum correlation with each other.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] CCA is now a cornerstone of multivariate statistics and multi-view learning, and a great number of interpretations and extensions have been proposed, such as probabilistic CCA, sparse CCA, multi-view CCA, deep CCA, and DeepGeoCCA.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] Unfortunately, perhaps because of its popularity, the literature can be inconsistent with notation.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] We attempt to highlight such inconsistencies in this article to help the reader make best use of the existing literature and techniques available.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] Like its sister method PCA, CCA can be viewed in *population* form (corresponding to random vectors and their covariance matrices) or in *sample* form (corresponding to datasets and their sample covariance matrices).
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] These two forms are almost exact analogues of each other, which is why their distinction is often overlooked, but they can behave very differently in high dimensional settings.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] We next give explicit mathematical definitions for the population problem and highlight the different objects in the so-called *canonical decomposition* - understanding the differences between these objects is crucial for interpretation of the technique.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] In practice, we would estimate the covariance matrix based on sampled data from X and Y (i.e. from a pair of data matrices).
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] Canonical-correlation analysis seeks a sequence of vectors $a_{k}$ ( $a_{k}\in \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ ) and $b_{k}$ ( $b_{k}\in \mathbb {R} ^{m}$ ) such that the random variables $a_{k}^{T}X$ and $b_{k}^{T}Y$ maximize the correlation $\rho =\operatorname {corr} (a_{k}^{T}X,b_{k}^{T}Y)$ .
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] The (scalar) random variables $U=a_{1}^{T}X$ and $V=b_{1}^{T}Y$ are the ***first pair of canonical variables***.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] Then one seeks vectors maximizing the same correlation subject to the constraint that they are to be uncorrelated with the first pair of canonical variables; this gives the ***second pair of canonical variables***.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] This procedure may be continued up to $\min\{m,n\}$ times.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] The sets of vectors $a_{k},b_{k}$ are called ***canonical directions*** or ***weight vectors*** or simply ***weights***.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] The 'dual' sets of vectors $\Sigma _{XX}a_{k},\Sigma _{YY}b_{k}$ are called ***canonical loading vectors*** or simply ***loadings***; these are often more straightforward to interpret than the weights.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] Let $\Sigma _{XY}$ be the cross-covariance matrix for any pair of (vector-shaped) random variables X and Y .
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] There is equality if the vectors d and $\Sigma _{YY}^{-1/2}\Sigma _{YX}\Sigma _{XX}^{-1/2}c$ are collinear.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] In addition, the maximum of correlation is attained if c is the eigenvector with the maximum eigenvalue for the matrix $\Sigma _{XX}^{-1/2}\Sigma _{XY}\Sigma _{YY}^{-1}\Sigma _{YX}\Sigma _{XX}^{-1/2}$ (see Rayleigh quotient).
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] The subsequent pairs are found by using eigenvalues of decreasing magnitudes.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] Orthogonality is guaranteed by the symmetry of the correlation matrices.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] Another way of viewing this computation is that c and d are the left and right singular vectors of the correlation matrix of X and Y corresponding to the highest singular value.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] CCA can be computed using singular value decomposition on a correlation matrix.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] CCA computation using singular value decomposition on a correlation matrix is related to the cosine of the angles between flats.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] The cosine function is ill-conditioned for small angles, leading to very inaccurate computation of highly correlated principal vectors in finite precision computer arithmetic.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] Each row can be tested for significance with the following method.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] Since the correlations are sorted, saying that row i is zero implies all further correlations are also zero.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] If we have p independent observations in a sample and ${\widehat {\rho }}_{i}$ is the estimated correlation for $i=1,\dots ,\min\{m,n\}$ .
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] which is asymptotically distributed as a chi-squared with $(m-i+1)(n-i+1)$ degrees of freedom for large p .
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] Since all the correlations from $\min\{m,n\}$ to p are logically zero (and estimated that way also) the product for the terms after this point is irrelevant.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] Note that in the small sample size limit with $p<n+m$ then we are guaranteed that the top $m+n-p$ correlations will be identically 1 and hence the test is meaningless.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] A typical use for canonical correlation in the experimental context is to take two sets of variables and see what is common among the two sets.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] For example, in psychological testing, one could take two well established multidimensional personality tests such as the Minnesota Multiphasic Personality Inventory (MMPI-2) and the NEO.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] By seeing how the MMPI-2 factors relate to the NEO factors, one could gain insight into what dimensions were common between the tests and how much variance was shared.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] For example, one might find that an extraversion or neuroticism dimension accounted for a substantial amount of shared variance between the two tests.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] One can also use canonical-correlation analysis to produce a model equation which relates two sets of variables, for example a set of performance measures and a set of explanatory variables, or a set of outputs and set of inputs.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] Constraint restrictions can be imposed on such a model to ensure it reflects theoretical requirements or intuitively obvious conditions.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] This type of model is known as a maximum correlation model.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] Visualization of the results of canonical correlation is usually through bar plots of the coefficients of the two sets of variables for the pairs of canonical variates showing significant correlation.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] Some authors suggest that they are best visualized by plotting them as heliographs, a circular format with ray like bars, with each half representing the two sets of variables.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] If $Y=-X$ , i.e., X and Y are perfectly anticorrelated, then, e.g., $a=1$ and $b=-1$ , so that the first (and only in this example) pair of canonical variables is $U=X$ and $V=-Y=X$ .
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] We notice that in both cases $U=V$ , which illustrates that the canonical-correlation analysis treats correlated and anticorrelated variables similarly.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] In this interpretation, the random variables, entries $x_{i}$ of X and $y_{j}$ of Y are treated as elements of a vector space with an inner product given by the covariance $\operatorname {cov} (x_{i},y_{j})$ ; see Covariance#Relationship to inner products.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] The definition of the canonical variables U and V is then equivalent to the definition of principal vectors for the pair of subspaces spanned by the entries of X and Y with respect to this inner product.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] The canonical correlations $\operatorname {corr} (U,V)$ is equal to the cosine of principal angles.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] CCA can also be viewed as a special whitening transformation where the random vectors X and Y are simultaneously transformed in such a way that the cross-correlation between the whitened vectors $X^{CCA}$ and $Y^{CCA}$ is diagonal.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] The canonical correlations are then interpreted as regression coefficients linking $X^{CCA}$ and $Y^{CCA}$ and may also be negative.
[src:canonical-correlation/canonical-correlation] The regression view of CCA also provides a way to construct a latent variable probabilistic generative model for CCA, with uncorrelated hidden variables representing shared and non-shared variability.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] In statistics, **correlation** is a type of statistical relationship between two random variables or bivariate data.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] It usually refers to the extent to which a pair of quantities are linearly related.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] More generally, an arbitrary relationship between variables is called an **association**, meaning the degree to which the variability in one can be accounted for by the other.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] The presence of a correlation is not sufficient to infer the presence of a causal relationship, and this is often stated as "correlation does not imply causation".
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Furthermore, the concept of correlation is not the same as dependence: if two variables are independent, then they are uncorrelated, but the opposite is not necessarily true – even if two variables are uncorrelated, they might be dependent on each other.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Correlations are useful because they can indicate a predictive relationship that can be exploited in practice.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] For example, an electrical utility may produce less power on a mild day based on the correlation between electricity demand and weather.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] In this example, there is a causal relationship, because extreme weather causes people to use more electricity for heating or cooling.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] There are several correlation coefficients that may be used to measure correlation, often denoted $\rho$ or r .
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] The most common of these is the **Pearson correlation coefficient**, which is sensitive only to a linear relationship between two variables (which in turn may be present even when one variable is a nonlinear function of the other).
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Other correlation coefficients, such as **Spearman's rank correlation coefficient**, have been developed to be more robust than Pearson's and to detect less structured relationships between variables.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] The concept has been generalized to other forms of association between two variables, such as mutual information and distance covariance.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] The most familiar measure of dependence between two quantities is the Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient, most commonly called 'Pearson's correlation coefficient' or simply 'the correlation coefficient' (as it is the most common variant).
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] It is obtained by taking the ratio of the covariance between two variables of a numerical dataset normalized to the square root of their variances.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Equivalently, Pearson's correlation coefficient can be calculated by dividing the covariance of the two variables by the product of their standard deviations.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Karl Pearson developed the coefficient from a similar idea by Francis Galton.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] A Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient attempts to establish a line of best fit through a dataset of two variables by essentially laying out the expected values and the resulting Pearson's correlation coefficient indicates how far away the actual dataset is from the expected values.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Depending on the sign of the Pearson's correlation coefficient, the result can be either a negative or positive correlation if there is any sort of relationship between the variables in the data set.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] where $\operatorname {E}$ is the expected value operator, $\operatorname {cov}$ means covariance, and $\operatorname {corr}$ is a widely used alternative notation for the correlation coefficient.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] The Pearson correlation is defined only if both standard deviations are finite and positive.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] It is a corollary of the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality that the absolute value of the Pearson correlation coefficient is not bigger than 1.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Therefore, the value of a correlation coefficient ranges between −1 and +1.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] As it approaches zero there is less of a relationship (closer to uncorrelated).
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] The closer the coefficient is to either −1 or 1, the stronger the correlation between the variables.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] If the variables are independent, Pearson's correlation coefficient is 0.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] However, because the correlation coefficient detects only linear dependencies between two variables, the converse is not necessarily true.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] A correlation coefficient of 0 does not imply that the variables are independent.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] For example, suppose the random variable X is symmetrically distributed about zero, and $Y=X^{2}$ .
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Then Y is completely determined by X , so that X and Y are perfectly dependent, but their correlation is zero; they are uncorrelated.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] However, in the special case when X and Y are jointly normal, uncorrelatedness is equivalent to independence.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Even though uncorrelated data does not necessarily imply independence, one can check if random variables are independent if their mutual information is 0.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Given a series of n measurements of the pair $(X_{i},Y_{i})$ indexed by $i=1,\ldots ,n$ , the *sample correlation coefficient* can be used to estimate the population Pearson correlation $\rho _{X,Y}$ between X and Y .
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] where ${\overline {x}}$ and ${\overline {y}}$ are the sample means of X and Y , and $s_{x}$ and $s_{y}$ are the corrected sample standard deviations of X and Y .
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] where $s'_{x}$ and $s'_{y}$ are the *uncorrected* sample standard deviations of X and Y .
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] If x and y are results of measurements that contain measurement error, the realistic limits on the correlation coefficient are not −1 to +1 but a smaller range.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] For the case of a linear model with a single independent variable, the coefficient of determination (R squared) is the square of $r_{xy}$ , Pearson's product-moment coefficient.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Consider the joint probability distribution of X and Y given in the table below.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Rank correlation coefficients, such as Spearman's rank correlation coefficient and Kendall's rank correlation coefficient (τ) measure the extent to which, as one variable increases, the other variable tends to increase, without requiring that increase to be represented by a linear relationship.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] If, as the one variable increases, the other *decreases*, the rank correlation coefficients will be negative.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] It is common to regard these rank correlation coefficients as alternatives to Pearson's coefficient, used either to reduce the amount of calculation or to make the coefficient less sensitive to non-normality in distributions.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] As we go from each pair to the next pair, x increases, and so does y .
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] This relationship is perfect, in the sense that an increase in x is *always* accompanied by an increase in y .
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] This means that we have a perfect rank correlation, and both Spearman's and Kendall's correlation coefficients are 1, whereas in this example Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient is 0.7544, indicating that the points are far from lying on a straight line.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] In the same way if y always *decreases* when x *increases*, the rank correlation coefficients will be −1, while the Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient may or may not be close to −1, depending on how close the points are to a straight line.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Although in the extreme cases of perfect rank correlation the two coefficients are both equal (being both +1 or both −1), this is not generally the case, and so values of the two coefficients cannot meaningfully be compared.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] For example, for the three pairs (1, 1) (2, 3) (3, 2) Spearman's coefficient is 1/2, while Kendall's coefficient is 1/3.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] The conventional dictum that "correlation does not imply causation" means that correlation cannot be used by itself to infer a causal relationship between the variables.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] This dictum should not be taken to mean that correlations cannot indicate the potential existence of causal relations.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] However, the causes underlying the correlation, if any, may be indirect and unknown, and high correlations also overlap with identity relations (tautologies), where no causal process exists (e.g., between two variables measuring the same construct).
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Consequently, a correlation between two variables is not a sufficient condition to establish a causal relationship (in either direction).
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] A correlation between age and height in children is fairly causally transparent, but a correlation between mood and health in people is less so.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Does improved mood lead to improved health, or does good health lead to good mood, or both?
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Or does some other factor underlie both?
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] In other words, a correlation can be taken as evidence for a possible causal relationship, but cannot indicate what the causal relationship, if any, might be.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] The Pearson correlation coefficient indicates the strength of a *linear* relationship between two variables, but its value generally does not completely characterize their relationship.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] In particular, if the conditional mean of Y given X , denoted $\operatorname {E} (Y\mid X)$ , is not linear in X , the correlation coefficient will not fully determine the form of $\operatorname {E} (Y\mid X)$ .
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] The adjacent image shows scatter plots of Anscombe's quartet, a set of four different pairs of variables created by Francis Anscombe.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] The four y variables have the same mean (7.5), variance (4.12), correlation (0.816) and regression line ( ${\textstyle y=3+0.5x}$ ).
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] However, as can be seen on the plots, the distribution of the variables is very different.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] The first one (top left) seems to be distributed normally, and corresponds to what one would expect when considering two variables correlated and following the assumption of normality.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] The second one (top right) is not distributed normally; while an obvious relationship between the two variables can be observed, it is not linear.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] In this case the Pearson correlation coefficient does not indicate that there is an exact functional relationship: only the extent to which that relationship can be approximated by a linear relationship.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] In the third case (bottom left), the linear relationship is perfect, except for one outlier which exerts enough influence to lower the correlation coefficient from 1 to 0.816.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Finally, the fourth example (bottom right) shows another example when one outlier is enough to produce a high correlation coefficient, even though the relationship between the two variables is not linear.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] These examples indicate that the correlation coefficient, as a summary statistic, cannot replace visual examination of the data.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] The examples are sometimes said to demonstrate that the Pearson correlation assumes that the data follow a normal distribution, but this is only partially correct.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] The Pearson correlation can be accurately calculated for any distribution that has a finite covariance matrix, which includes most distributions encountered in practice.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] However, the Pearson correlation coefficient (taken together with the sample mean and variance) is only a sufficient statistic if the data is drawn from a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] As a result, the Pearson correlation coefficient fully characterizes the relationship between variables if and only if the data are drawn from a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Similarly for two stochastic processes $\left\{X_{t}\right\}_{t\in {\mathcal {T}}}$ and $\left\{Y_{t}\right\}_{t\in {\mathcal {T}}}$ : If they are independent, then they are uncorrelated.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] The opposite of this statement might not be true.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Even if two variables are uncorrelated, they might not be independent of each other.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] The degree of dependence between variables X and Y does not depend on the scale on which the variables are expressed.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] That is, if we are analyzing the relationship between X and Y, most correlation measures are unaffected by transforming X to *a* + *bX* and Y to *c* + *dY*, where *a*, *b*, *c*, and *d* are constants (*b* and *d* being positive).
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] This is true of some correlation statistics as well as their population analogues.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Some correlation statistics, such as the rank correlation coefficient, are also invariant to monotone transformations of the marginal distributions of X and/or Y.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Most correlation measures are sensitive to the manner in which X and Y are sampled.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Dependencies tend to be stronger if viewed over a wider range of values.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Several techniques have been developed that attempt to correct for range restriction in one or both variables, and are commonly used in meta-analysis; the most common are Thorndike's case II and case III equations.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Various correlation measures in use may be undefined for certain joint distributions of X and Y.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] For example, the Pearson correlation coefficient is defined in terms of moments, and hence will be undefined if the moments are undefined.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Measures of dependence based on quantiles are always defined.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Sample-based statistics intended to estimate population measures of dependence may or may not have desirable statistical properties such as being unbiased, or asymptotically consistent, based on the spatial structure of the population from which the data were sampled.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Sensitivity to the data distribution can be used to an advantage.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] For example, scaled correlation is designed to use the sensitivity to the range in order to pick out correlations between fast components of time series.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] By reducing the range of values in a controlled manner, the correlations on long time scale are filtered out and only the correlations on short time scales are revealed.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Thus the diagonal entries are all identically one.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] If the measures of correlation used are product-moment coefficients, the correlation matrix is the same as the covariance matrix of the standardized random variables $X_{i}/\sigma (X_{i})$ for $i=1,\dots ,n$ .
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] This applies both to the matrix of population correlations (in which case $\sigma$ is the population standard deviation), and to the matrix of sample correlations (in which case $\sigma$ denotes the sample standard deviation).
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Consequently, each is necessarily a positive-semidefinite matrix.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Moreover, the correlation matrix is strictly positive definite if no variable can have all its values exactly generated as a linear function of the values of the others.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] The correlation matrix is symmetric because the correlation between $X_{i}$ and $X_{j}$ is the same as the correlation between $X_{j}$ and $X_{i}$ .
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] A correlation matrix appears, for example, in one formula for the coefficient of multiple determination, a measure of goodness of fit in multiple regression.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] In statistical modelling, correlation matrices representing the relationships between variables are categorized into different correlation structures, which are distinguished by factors such as the number of parameters required to estimate them.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] For example, in an exchangeable correlation matrix, all pairs of variables are modeled as having the same correlation, so all non-diagonal elements of the matrix are equal to each other.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] On the other hand, an autoregressive matrix is often used when variables represent a time series, since correlations are likely to be greater when measurements are closer in time.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Other examples include independent, unstructured, M-dependent, and Toeplitz.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] In exploratory data analysis, the iconography of correlations consists in replacing a correlation matrix by a diagram where the "remarkable" correlations are represented by a solid line (positive correlation), or a dotted line (negative correlation).
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] In some applications (e.g., building data models from only partially observed data) one wants to find the "nearest" correlation matrix to an "approximate" correlation matrix (e.g., a matrix which typically lacks positive semi-definiteness due to the way it has been computed).
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] In 2002, Higham formalized the notion of nearness using the Frobenius norm and provided a method for computing the nearest correlation matrix using the Dykstra's projection algorithm.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] This sparked interest in the subject, with new theoretical (e.g., computing the nearest correlation matrix with factor structure) and numerical (e.g. usage of Newton's method for computing the nearest correlation matrix) results obtained in the subsequent years.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] where $\operatorname {\boldsymbol {\mathcal {E}}} (X)$ and $\operatorname {\boldsymbol {\mathcal {E}}} (Y)$ are the expected values of $\ X\$ and $\ Y\ ,$ respectively, and $\ \sigma _{X}\$ and $\ \sigma _{Y}\$ are the standard deviations of $\ X\$ and $\ Y\ ,$ respectively.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] where $\ F_{Hyp}\$ is the Gaussian hypergeometric function.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] This density is both a Bayesian posterior density and an exact optimal confidence distribution density.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] The information given by a correlation coefficient is not enough to define the dependence structure between random variables.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] The correlation coefficient completely defines the dependence structure only in very particular cases, for example when the distribution is a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] (See diagram above.) In the case of elliptical distributions it characterizes the (hyper-)ellipses of equal density; however, it does not completely characterize the dependence structure (for example, a multivariate t-distribution's degrees of freedom determine the level of tail dependence).
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] For continuous variables, multiple alternative measures of dependence were introduced to address the deficiency of Pearson's correlation that it can be zero for dependent random variables (see and references therein for an overview).
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] They all share the important property that a value of zero implies independence.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] This led some authors to recommend their routine usage, particularly of distance correlation.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Another alternative measure is the Randomized Dependence Coefficient.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] The RDC is a computationally efficient, copula-based measure of dependence between multivariate random variables and is invariant with respect to non-linear scalings of random variables.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] One important disadvantage of the alternative, more general measures is that, when used to test whether two variables are associated, they tend to have lower power compared to Pearson's correlation when the data follow a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] This is an implication of the No free lunch theorem.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] To detect all kinds of relationships, these measures have to sacrifice power on other relationships, particularly for the important special case of a linear relationship with Gaussian marginals, for which Pearson's correlation is optimal.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Another problem concerns interpretation.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] While Pearson's correlation can be interpreted for all values, the alternative measures can generally only be interpreted meaningfully at the extremes.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] For two binary variables, the odds ratio measures their dependence, and takes a range of non-negative numbers, possibly infinity: ⁠ $[0,+\infty ]$ ⁠.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] Related statistics such as Yule's *Y* and Yule's *Q* normalize this to the correlation-like range ⁠ $[-1,1]$ ⁠.
[src:canonical-correlation/correlation] The odds ratio is generalized by the logistic model to model cases where the dependent variables are discrete and there may be one or more independent variables.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] In probability theory and statistics, a **covariance matrix** (also known as **auto-covariance matrix**, **dispersion matrix**, **variance matrix**, or **variance–covariance matrix**) is a square matrix giving the covariance between each pair of elements of a given random vector.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] Intuitively, the covariance matrix generalizes the notion of variance to multiple dimensions.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] Any covariance matrix is symmetric and positive semi-definite and its main diagonal contains variances (i.e., the covariance of each element with itself).
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] The covariance matrix of a random vector $\mathbf {X}$ is typically denoted by $\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {X} \mathbf {X} }$ , $\Sigma$ or S .
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] Throughout this article, boldfaced unsubscripted $\mathbf {X}$ and $\mathbf {Y}$ are used to refer to random vectors, and Roman subscripted $X_{i}$ and $Y_{i}$ are used to refer to scalar random variables.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] Both forms are quite standard, and there is no ambiguity between them.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] The matrix $\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {X} \mathbf {X} }$ is also often called the **variance-covariance matrix**, since the diagonal terms are in fact variances.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] Each element on the principal diagonal of a correlation matrix is the correlation of a random variable with itself, which always equals 1.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] Each off-diagonal element is between −1 and +1 inclusive.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] The inverse of this matrix, $\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {X} \mathbf {X} }^{-1}$ , if it exists, is the inverse covariance matrix, also known as the *precision matrix* (or *concentration matrix*).
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] This duality motivates a number of other dualities between marginalizing and conditioning for Gaussian random variables.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] $\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {XX} }$ and $\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {YY} }$ can be identified as the variance matrices of the marginal distributions for $\mathbf {X}$ and $\mathbf {Y}$ respectively.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] The matrix $\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {YX} }\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {XX} }^{-1}$ is known as the matrix of regression coefficients, while in linear algebra $\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {Y|X} }$ is the Schur complement of $\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {XX} }$ in ${\boldsymbol {\Sigma }}$ .
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] In this form they correspond to the coefficients obtained by inverting the matrix of the normal equations of ordinary least squares (OLS).
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] A covariance matrix with all non-zero elements tells us that all the individual random variables are interrelated.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] This means that the variables are not only directly correlated, but also correlated via other variables indirectly.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] Often such indirect, common-mode correlations are trivial and uninteresting.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] They can be suppressed by calculating the partial covariance matrix, that is the part of covariance matrix that shows only the interesting part of correlations.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] The standard deviation matrix $\mathbf {S}$ is the extension of the standard deviation to multiple dimensions.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] It is the symmetric square root of the covariance matrix $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ .
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] Applied to one vector, the covariance matrix maps a linear combination **c** of the random variables **X** onto a vector of covariances with those variables: $\mathbf {c} ^{\mathsf {T}}\Sigma =\operatorname {cov} (\mathbf {c} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {X} ,\mathbf {X} )$ .
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] Treated as a bilinear form, it yields the covariance between the two linear combinations: $\mathbf {d} ^{\mathsf {T}}{\boldsymbol {\Sigma }}\mathbf {c} =\operatorname {cov} (\mathbf {d} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {X} ,\mathbf {c} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {X} )$ .
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] The variance of a linear combination is then $\mathbf {c} ^{\mathsf {T}}{\boldsymbol {\Sigma }}\mathbf {c}$ , its covariance with itself.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] Similarly, the (pseudo-)inverse covariance matrix provides an inner product $\langle c-\mu |\Sigma ^{+}|c-\mu \rangle$ , which induces the Mahalanobis distance, a measure of the "unlikelihood" of *c*.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] Conversely, every symmetric positive semi-definite matrix is a covariance matrix.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] To see this, suppose M is a $p\times p$ symmetric positive-semidefinite matrix.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] From the finite-dimensional case of the spectral theorem, it follows that M has a nonnegative symmetric square root, which can be denoted by **M**1/2.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] Let $\mathbf {X}$ be any $p\times 1$ column vector-valued random variable whose covariance matrix is the $p\times p$ identity matrix.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] If $\mathbf {Z} =(Z_{1},\ldots ,Z_{n})^{\mathsf {T}}$ is a column vector of complex-valued random variables, then the conjugate transpose $\mathbf {Z} ^{\mathsf {H}}$ is formed by *both* transposing and conjugating.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] In contrast to the covariance matrix defined above, Hermitian transposition gets replaced by transposition in the definition.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] Its diagonal elements may be complex valued; it is a complex symmetric matrix.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] These empirical sample covariance matrices are the most straightforward and most often used estimators for the covariance matrices, but other estimators also exist, including regularised or shrinkage estimators, which may have better properties.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] The covariance matrix is a useful tool in many different areas.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] This is called principal component analysis (PCA) and the Karhunen–Loève transform (KL-transform).
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] The covariance matrix plays a key role in financial economics, especially in portfolio theory and its mutual fund separation theorem and in the capital asset pricing model.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] The matrix of covariances among various assets' returns is used to determine, under certain assumptions, the relative amounts of different assets that investors should (in a normative analysis) or are predicted to (in a positive analysis) choose to hold in a context of diversification.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] The evolution strategy, a particular family of Randomized Search Heuristics, fundamentally relies on a covariance matrix in its mechanism.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] The characteristic mutation operator draws the update step from a multivariate normal distribution using an evolving covariance matrix.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] Intuitively, this result is supported by the rationale that the optimal covariance distribution can offer mutation steps whose equidensity probability contours match the level sets of the landscape, and so they maximize the progress rate.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] In **covariance mapping** the values of the $\operatorname {cov} (\mathbf {X} ,\mathbf {Y} )$ or $\operatorname {pcov} (\mathbf {X} ,\mathbf {Y} \mid \mathbf {I} )$ matrix are plotted as a 2-dimensional map.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] When vectors $\mathbf {X}$ and $\mathbf {Y}$ are discrete random functions, the map shows statistical relations between different regions of the random functions.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] Statistically independent regions of the functions show up on the map as zero-level flatland, while positive or negative correlations show up, respectively, as hills or valleys.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] 1 illustrates how a partial covariance map is constructed on an example of an experiment performed at the FLASH free-electron laser in Hamburg.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] The random function $X(t)$ is the time-of-flight spectrum of ions from a Coulomb explosion of nitrogen molecules multiply ionised by a laser pulse.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] Since only a few hundreds of molecules are ionised at each laser pulse, the single-shot spectra are highly fluctuating.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] However, collecting typically $m=10^{4}$ such spectra, $\mathbf {X} _{j}(t)$ , and averaging them over j produces a smooth spectrum $\langle \mathbf {X} (t)\rangle$ , which is shown in red at the bottom of Fig.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] The average spectrum $\langle \mathbf {X} \rangle$ reveals several nitrogen ions in a form of peaks broadened by their kinetic energy, but to find the correlations between the ionisation stages and the ion momenta requires calculating a covariance map.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] 1 spectra $\mathbf {X} _{j}(t)$ and $\mathbf {Y} _{j}(t)$ are the same, except that the range of the time-of-flight t differs.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] Panel **a** shows $\langle \mathbf {XY^{\mathsf {T}}} \rangle$ , panel **b** shows $\langle \mathbf {X} \rangle \langle \mathbf {Y} ^{\mathsf {T}}\rangle$ and panel **c** shows their difference, which is $\operatorname {cov} (\mathbf {X} ,\mathbf {Y} )$ (note a change in the colour scale).
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] Unfortunately, this map is overwhelmed by uninteresting, common-mode correlations induced by laser intensity fluctuating from shot to shot.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] To suppress such correlations the laser intensity $I_{j}$ is recorded at every shot, put into $\mathbf {I}$ and $\operatorname {pcov} (\mathbf {X} ,\mathbf {Y} \mid \mathbf {I} )$ is calculated as panels **d** and **e** show.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] The suppression of the uninteresting correlations is, however, imperfect because there are other sources of common-mode fluctuations than the laser intensity and in principle all these sources should be monitored in vector $\mathbf {I}$ .
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] Yet in practice it is often sufficient to overcompensate the partial covariance correction as panel **f** shows, where interesting correlations of ion momenta are now clearly visible as straight lines centred on ionisation stages of atomic nitrogen.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] Two-dimensional infrared spectroscopy employs correlation analysis to obtain 2D spectra of the condensed phase.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] There are two versions of this analysis: synchronous and asynchronous.
[src:canonical-correlation/covariance-matrix] Mathematically, the former is expressed in terms of the sample covariance matrix and the technique is equivalent to covariance mapping.
[src:canonical-correlation/cross-covariance] In probability and statistics, given two stochastic processes $\left\{X_{t}\right\}$ and $\left\{Y_{t}\right\}$ , the **cross-covariance** is a function that gives the covariance of one process with the other at pairs of time points.
[src:canonical-correlation/cross-covariance] Cross-covariance is related to the more commonly used cross-correlation of the processes in question.
[src:canonical-correlation/cross-covariance] In signal processing, the cross-covariance is often called cross-correlation and is a measure of similarity of two signals, commonly used to find features in an unknown signal by comparing it to a known one.
[src:canonical-correlation/cross-covariance] It is a function of the relative time between the signals, is sometimes called the *sliding dot product*, and has applications in pattern recognition and cryptanalysis.
[src:canonical-correlation/cross-covariance] Two stochastic processes $\left\{X_{t}\right\}$ and $\left\{Y_{t}\right\}$ are called **uncorrelated** if their covariance $\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {X} \mathbf {Y} }(t_{1},t_{2})$ is zero for all times.
[src:canonical-correlation/cross-covariance] The cross-covariance is also relevant in signal processing where the cross-covariance between two wide-sense stationary random processes can be estimated by averaging the product of samples measured from one process and samples measured from the other (and its time shifts).
[src:canonical-correlation/cross-covariance] The samples included in the average can be an arbitrary subset of all the samples in the signal (e.g., samples within a finite time window or a sub-sampling of one of the signals).
[src:canonical-correlation/cross-covariance] For a large number of samples, the average converges to the true covariance.
[src:canonical-correlation/cross-covariance] Cross-covariance may also refer to a **"deterministic" cross-covariance** between two signals.
[src:canonical-correlation/cross-covariance] This consists of summing over *all* time indices.
[src:canonical-correlation/cross-covariance] where the line indicates that the complex conjugate is taken when the signals are complex-valued.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Multivariate analysis can be complicated by the desire to include physics-based analysis to calculate the effects of variables for a hierarchical "system-of-systems".
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Often, studies that wish to use multivariate analysis are stalled by the dimensionality of the problem.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] These concerns are often eased through the use of surrogate models, highly accurate approximations of the physics-based code.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Since surrogate models take the form of an equation, they can be evaluated very quickly.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] This becomes an enabler for large-scale MVA studies: while a Monte Carlo simulation across the design space is difficult with physics-based codes, it becomes trivial when evaluating surrogate models, which often take the form of response-surface equations.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Multivariate regression attempts to determine a formula that can describe how elements in a vector of variables respond simultaneously to changes in others.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] For linear relations, regression analyses here are based on forms of the general linear model.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Some suggest that multivariate regression is distinct from multivariable regression, however, that is debated and not consistently true across scientific fields.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Principal components analysis (PCA) creates a new set of orthogonal variables that contain the same information as the original set.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] It rotates the axes of variation to give a new set of orthogonal axes, ordered so that they summarize decreasing proportions of the variation.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Factor analysis is similar to PCA but allows the user to extract a specified number of synthetic variables, fewer than the original set, leaving the remaining unexplained variation as error.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] The extracted variables are known as latent variables or factors; each one may be supposed to account for covariation in a group of observed variables.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Canonical correlation analysis finds linear relationships among two sets of variables; it is the generalised (i.e. canonical) version of bivariate correlation.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Redundancy analysis (RDA) is similar to canonical correlation analysis but allows the user to derive a specified number of synthetic variables from one set of (independent) variables that explain as much variance as possible in another (independent) set.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] It is a multivariate analogue of regression.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Correspondence analysis (CA), or reciprocal averaging, finds (like PCA) a set of synthetic variables that summarise the original set.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] The underlying model assumes chi-squared dissimilarities among records (cases).
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Canonical (or "constrained") correspondence analysis (CCA) for summarising the joint variation in two sets of variables (like redundancy analysis); combination of correspondence analysis and multivariate regression analysis.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Multidimensional scaling comprises various algorithms to determine a set of synthetic variables that best represent the pairwise distances between records.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] The original method is principal coordinates analysis (PCoA; based on PCA).
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Discriminant analysis, or canonical variate analysis, attempts to establish whether a set of variables can be used to distinguish between two or more groups of cases.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Linear discriminant analysis (LDA) computes a linear predictor from two sets of normally distributed data to allow for classification of new observations.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Clustering systems assign objects into groups (called clusters) so that objects (cases) from the same cluster are more similar to each other than objects from different clusters.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Recursive partitioning creates a decision tree that attempts to correctly classify members of the population based on a dichotomous dependent variable.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Artificial neural networks extend regression and clustering methods to non-linear multivariate models.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Statistical graphics such as tours, parallel coordinate plots, scatterplot matrices can be used to explore multivariate data.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Simultaneous equations models involve more than one regression equation, with different dependent variables, estimated together.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Vector autoregression involves simultaneous regressions of various time series variables on their own and each other's lagged values.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Principal response curves analysis (PRC) is a method based on RDA that allows the user to focus on treatment effects over time by correcting for changes in control treatments over time.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Iconography of correlations consists in replacing a correlation matrix by a diagram where the "remarkable" correlations are represented by a solid line (positive correlation), or a dotted line (negative correlation).
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] It is very common that in an experimentally acquired set of data the values of some components of a given data point are missing.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Rather than discarding the whole data point, it is common to "fill in" values for the missing components, a process called "imputation".
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] There is a set of probability distributions used in multivariate analyses that play a similar role to the corresponding set of distributions that are used in univariate analysis when the normal distribution is appropriate to a dataset.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] The Inverse-Wishart distribution is important in Bayesian inference, for example in Bayesian multivariate linear regression.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Additionally, Hotelling's T-squared distribution is a multivariate distribution, generalising Student's t-distribution, that is used in multivariate hypothesis testing.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Rao made significant contributions to multivariate statistical theory throughout his career, particularly in the mid-20th century.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] One of his key works is the book titled "Advanced Statistical Methods in Biometric Research," published in 1952.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] This work laid the foundation for many concepts in multivariate statistics.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] Anderson's 1958 textbook,*An Introduction to Multivariate Statistical Analysis*, educated a generation of theorists and applied statisticians; Anderson's book emphasizes hypothesis testing via likelihood ratio tests and the properties of power functions: admissibility, unbiasedness and monotonicity.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] MVA was formerly discussed solely in the context of statistical theories, due to the size and complexity of underlying datasets and its high computational consumption.
[src:canonical-correlation/multivariate-statistics] With the dramatic growth of computational power, MVA now plays an increasingly important role in data analysis and has wide application in Omics fields.
